<section xml:id="Pacific_Island_Navigation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Pacific Island Navigation</title>
    <introduction>
  <p>
    Pacific Islanders have been navigating across long distances in the Pacific long 
    before the magnetic compasses or other modern instruments were introduced. 
    Navigators relied on observations of the stars, sun, ocean, winds, habits of sea 
    and winged creatures, and other terrestrial and marine signs from nature to 
    determine their position relative to the direction of known or meaningful 
    locales – islands, reefs, continents – around them. Through time, much of the art 
    and science of traditional navigating was lost across the Pacific, except in some 
    islands, mostly in Micronesia and on the island of Taumako in the Solomon Islands, 
    where traditional schools continued to produce ocean going canoes and 
    individuals – navigators – capable of voyaging long distances through the 
    instrumentalization of deep knowledge about the natural world. 
  </p>
    </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Micronesia">
    <title>Micronesia</title>

    <p>
      Navigators in Micronesia use the <em>paafu</em><idx><h>paafu</h></idx> mat or 
      map (shown in <xref ref="paafu">Figure</xref>), often mistranslated and misconstrued as a Star 
      <q>Compass</q> for its use of stars and constellations to discern direction, but 
      paafu is similar but not equivalent to the use of stars to mark cardinal 
      directionality (the familiar marking of space in terms of North, South, East and 
      West <q>cardinal points</q> for which compasses are known). Instead, paafu is a 
      learning and teaching tool that was developed to begin to teach the locational 
      position of an island (or a locale, or even a canoe) relative to other locales 
      as these are <q>marked</q> by rising and setting points of stars and constellations. 
    </p>

