<p>
A constellation is a cluster of stars whose shapes and meanings reflect and carry 
cultural meanings or significance, such as the cluster of stars, prominent in the 
southern hemisphere, that is cruciform in shape and is commonly referred to in modern 
society as the <q>Southern Cross.</q> The same constellation for the Polowatese and other 
islanders from the Central Carolines region in the western Pacific islands resembles 
for them the trigger fish Pup, and so is named as such. In the Central Carolines, the 
general location in the celestial sky where stars appear to rise after sundown is 
referred to as <q><em>tan</em>,</q> which is often mistranslated as <q>east</q> since 
modern society refers to stars (like the sun) as <q>rising</q> in the east. Indeed, tan 
means <q>rising.</q> It does not mean <q>Eastward.</q>
</p>

<p>
<xref ref="paafu">Figure</xref> orients the cardinal direction known as <q>east</q> at the top of 
the page, and so the top half of this diagram is also identified as <q>tan</q> – where 
stars appear to rise. Following an apparent <q>path</q> across the sky each night and 
day (although most stars are not visible during the day) and across a year – in this 
system, the rising and presence of specific stars across the sky mark months, the same 
stars will eventually set at a point horizontally opposite where they rose. 
Corresponding to the cardinal direction point called <q>west,</q> this part of the circle 
is referred to as <q><em>tolon</em></q> or where the stars <q>set</q> or go down. In the 
paafu <q>map</q> in <xref ref="paafu">Figure</xref>, whose center is the figure of a canoe, the 
star called Mailap (Altair) marks due east. Where and when Mailap rises is referred 
to as Tan Mailap (rising Mailap) and when and where it sets is referred to as Tolon 
Mailap (setting Mailap). In <xref ref="paafu">Figure</xref>, east or the rising points of the 
navigation or paafu stars is situated at the top of the circle, and west or the setting 
points of these stars is situated at the bottom of the circle. As a map, paafu uses the 
rising and setting points of stars to mark places around any given locale that would be 
placed in the center of the circle (see <xref ref="tab_paafu">Table</xref>). Paafu can also be used 
to identify the direction that moving objects, like canoes, or creatures, like birds, 
fish, and humans, are heading or coming from. In this version of paafu, the stars are 
identified using the Polowat dialect of the Chuukese language as it is used by members 
of the Weriyeng School of navigation.
    </p>

