  <p>
    In the star compass, whose center is the figure of an ʻiwa or great frigatebird, 
    Thompson divides the visual horizon into 32 equidistant points around a circle, 
    called houses. The houses in the Hawaiian Star Compass represent a space on the 
    horizon (<m>11.25^{\circ}</m>) where celestial bodies such as the sun, stars, 
    moon, and planets rise and set. In the same way that we have addresses to help 
    people find our homes, each celestial body has its own address represented with 
    these houses.
  </p>
  <p>
    The four cardinal points correspond to a house.
    The stars arrive from the horizon called <em>Hikina</em>
    (<q>To Arrive</q>) or East and enter the horizon called <em>Komohana</em>
    (<q>To Enter</q>) or West.
    If you stand with your back towards Hikina (East) and face Komohana (West),
    your right will point towards <em>ʻĀkau</em>
    (<q>Right</q>) or North and your left will point towards <em>Hema</em>
    (<q>Left</q>) or South. The Hawaiian Star Compass is oriented with North at 
    the top of the compass.
  </p>
  <p>
    These four cardinal points divide the compass into four quadrants.
    Each quadrant is named after winds in Hawaiʻi.
    <em>Koʻolau</em> is the Northeast quadrant named for the trade winds;
    <em>Hoʻolua</em> is the Northwest quadrant,
    <em>Kona</em> is the Southwest quadrant;
    and <em>Malanai</em> is the Southeast quadrant.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each house on the compass has a name.
    The corresponding houses in the east and in the west share a name.
    Starting in the east or west and moving northwards and southwards 
    is the first house positioned on either side of Hikina (East) and Komohana (West).
    This is the house Lā (Sun).
    It is followed by ʻĀina (Land), Noio (Tern), Manu (Bird), Nālani (Heavens), Nā Leo (Voices),
    and Haka (Empty).
    The 32 houses in the Hawaiian Star Compass correspond to the points of the 32-wind compass rose
    (<xref ref="tab_compass">Table</xref>).
    The celestial bodies move in parallel paths across the sky from East to West,
    rising and setting in the same house,
    remaining in its hemisphere
    (<xref ref="fig_celestial-sphere">Figure</xref>).
  </p>
  
  <p>
    For example,
    if a star arrives in the Koʻolau (northeastern) quadrant in the star house ʻĀina,
    it will arc overhead,
    staying in the northern hemisphere and enters the horizon in the same house it arrived in, ʻĀina,
    but in the Hoʻolua (northwest) quadrant, see Figure <xref ref="fig_celestial-sphere"/>.
    If a star arrives in the Malanai (southeast) quadrant in the house Lā, it will remain in the southern hemisphere as it arcs overhead and enters the horizon in the house Lā in the Kona (southwestern) quadrant.
  </p>
  <figure xml:id="fig_celestial-sphere">
    <caption>
      In the Celestial Sphere, stars rise in the East, move over the sky and set in the West. 
      A star will rise and set in the same house.
    </caption>
    <interactive geogebra="nmjdg3kb" aspect="1.75:1"/>
  </figure>
  <p>
    The star compass is also used to determine direction based on wind and ocean swells.
    As the wind and swells move, they cross the star compass diagonally.
    If a wind is blowing from the house Noio in the Koʻolau (northeast) quadrant,
    it would blow in the direction of the Kona (southwest) quadrant and exit at the same house it originated from, Noio.
  </p>
  <p>
    Now that we know the star compass,
    you may be asking how do we tell direction?
    To do this, we use observations.
    At night, Thompson uses about 220 stars to tell direction,
    memorizing where they rise and set on horizon.
    During the day when the sun is low on the horizon,
    we can use the sun but as it gets higher,
    you no longer are able to tell where on the horizon it came from.
    You can also memorize where the wind and waves are coming from and check to see if it has changed direction between sunrise and sunset.
  </p>
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-marshall-islands">
  <title>Marshall Islands</title>
  <p>
    The Marshallese people use stick charts as navigational tools. These stick charts are indeed constructed using a 
    lattice-like structure made from curved and straight sticks, typically formed by tying together the midribs of 
    coconut fronds. The curved sticks represent the islands and how they bend and refract the ocean swells, 
    while the straight sticks symbolize the major wave patterns in the surrounding waters.
  </p>
  <p>
    The shells placed on the sticks indicate the relative locations of islands within the Marshall Islands archipelago. 
    These shells serve as markers, helping navigators remember the positions of specific islands along their voyages.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each stick chart is unique to its creator, reflecting their individual knowledge and experiences. 
    The personalization of the stick charts allows navigators to develop a deep understanding of the ocean currents, 
    wave patterns, and island locations in their specific region.
  </p>
  <p>
    The stick charts serve as mental maps or navigational aids, allowing experienced navigators to visualize and 
    recall the complex information while on their journeys. Navigators would memorize the stick charts, 
    internalizing the knowledge embedded within them, enabling them to navigate the open ocean.
  </p>
  <p>
    <figure width="75%" xml:id="marshallese-stick-chart">
      <caption>Marshallese stick chart.</caption>
      <image source="stick-chart.jpg"/>
    </figure>
  </p>
</subsection>
